y in the Hellenistic world and pagan opposition to both techniques. The remainder of the book presents three Hellenistic religious writers who each typify distinctive models of allegorical interpretation: the Jewish exegete Philo, the Christian Gnostic Valentinus, and the Christian Platonist Clement. The study engages issues in the fields of classics, history of Christianity and Hellenistic Judaism, literary criticism and theory, and more broadly, critical theory and cultural criticism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAllegory. 0aClassical literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aGnosticism. 0aReligion and culturezEgyptzAlexandria. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aallegorical interpretation.  aancient allegory.  aancient pagan.  achristian gnostic valentinus.  achristian platonist clement.  achristian.  aclassics.  acompeting religious views.  acounterreadings.  acritical theory.  aculture and society.  aetymology.  ahellenistic judaism.  ahellenistic world.  ahistory of christianity.  ajewish.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary texts.  aliterary theory.  anon literal readings.  aphilo.  areligious texts.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052007102540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520910386?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520910386423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520910386/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY